Coiling and twisting of shapes appear to the same extent in the interiors.
Wood in wool copies window frames, shelves, decorative elements of the door, hooks and rods.
The Batlló House, which is located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gràcia No. 43, was built by the renovation of the house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
Reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new one, but soon took Gaudí’s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batlló, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
He worked with architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on its design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade.
A number of other artists and artists worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs of Casa Batlló started a successful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and Güell Park, in which Gaudí's other works are included.
From the locals, the house of the bay after its completion earned the nickname "House of bones" thanks to its organic shapes.
Others called it a "living house" because of the specific mechanism of opening windows.
It is also said that at the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí proposed a unique central heating system with ventilation ducts and typical chimneys for his time.
Bizarre may seem to be their forty-five-degree slope.
During Gaudí’s creation, he did not comply with the construction regulations of that time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
Although at the beginning of the construction he was granted a building permit from the city, the data he provided on the planned reconstruction was so heavy that two years later on completion, the city council was devastated and requested correction.
For example, the council was disturbed by the fact that the building also interfered with the pillars in the public corridor.
On the contrary, it was never repaired: only fifteen days after the challenge of the district, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a communal living room and on the third floor a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented by jewelry.
The entire six-storey house runs across the staircase, which can be reached up to the rooftop terrace itself.
The main elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all the right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors and a larger society can communicate comfortably together without at the same time maintaining the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new façade, the house with Gaudí rebuilt also received an unconventional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudí’s play is also impressive with light, blue and white glazed tiles, with which the inner courtyard is covered, and candles.
The game of two colors provides maximum light in all floors of the house.
Simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun’s rays.
Casa Batlló, which was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and honorable apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the centenary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed for the tours because they found that it was a very profitable business and, in addition, the tours expanded on common and loft spaces, including the roof terrace.
