Longer indicator than ring indicates lower risk of cancer
Men who have a marker longer than the ring are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British Cancer Journal.
This can be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative finger length can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under the age of 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially in combination with genetic risk or other risk factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time more than 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a pointer on their right hand shorter than a ring.
They had the same likelihood of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were just as long.
For those who had an index longer than the ring, however, this risk decreased by 33 percent, and for men up to the age of sixties, a decrease of even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned - formed in the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer indicator.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that promotes growing prostate cancer.
A leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Václav Pa<0xC4><0x8D>es for <0xC4><0x8C>TK, said he knew about the study at the same time, but it does not appear to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "completely proven".
