These are some of the results of the current Latinobarometer survey, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
This year’s survey, which took place in September and early October, dominated two related matters.
The first is that Latin America is in a relatively happy mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the outskirts of the Pacific in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy recovered after a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents across the region expressed their satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, it is the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, it is a big increase (Chart 3).
Approximately 34% said they trust the parliament in their own country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but it’s a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis in Latin America undermined democracy.
Support was created during the global financial crisis, probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only negligiblely in 2009 and again fell to 32% this year.)
However, the mood changes in a wide spectrum from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its retiring President Luiza Inácia Luly da Silva are reflected in a broadly accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more serious and the state of violent crime has worsened.
