It resolves what type of damage such behavior affects the sporting spirit.
One of the attributes of athletic behavior is the physical inviolability of opponents, which was not violated in these cases, or there was no violent play.
Another of these features that characterize the pure game is to avoid the players from having an advantage over the opponent's team due to their violation - which is not the case here either.
So paradoxical to the Real Madrid player’s action is the fact that what we normally describe as a ladder or circumvention of the law, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid a penalty, but this behavior should be as visible as possible in order to receive the penalty.
They waited and liked to be punished.
The other question, however, is what advantage the culprits will have from their deliberate offense.
It should be noted here that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that in the current game he does not seek any benefit, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
Nor is this a useful strategy for another game, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in a future game.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, that is, at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition to this action, the players will be penalized, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which the exclusion is enough in the round of the penalty.
So as the wheels continue, it will not be entirely clear if this is an advantage.
In short, these actions are not against the sporting spirit, the part of which is to make a strategic decision that will allow to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
In the cases in which we are dealing here, the players were not aimed at avoiding the award of a penalty (which would be a clear circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
Although the boundary between the reasoning and the circumvention of the rules is not quite clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly a reasoning.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because these were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which instructions were transmitted to provoke them from the leadership.
Damage to sporting principles by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
