People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services centres even before an interview with the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the process of negotiating visas at the Embassy of the United States and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services (ASC) centres before an interview with the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will collect the applicant’s biometric information and will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new approach will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of issuing a visa will be lower, there will no longer be a fee for arranging a meeting, the second for processing the application and the other for delivering the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee that covers all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: <0x24>140 for tourist visas, <0x24>150 for visa applications (including visas for temporary workers) and <0x24>390 for trader and investor visas.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular official, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and get their fingerprints.
Since biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra <0x24>26 fee for the service.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for a visa, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
